# Swift Testing: tests belong in a suite

Swift unit tests that use Swift Testing must be **grouped in a suite**. **`@Test` must not appear at file top level.**

- Declare a **`@Suite`** type (struct or enum) and put **`@Test`** methods or static functions **inside** that type.
- Do not place **`@Test`** on free functions or properties at the root of the file.

```swift
// ❌ BAD — top-level @Test
import Testing

@Test func example() {
  #expect(true)
}
```

```swift
// ✅ GOOD — @Test inside @Suite
import Testing

struct ExampleTests {
  @Test func example() {
    #expect(true)
  }
}
```

If you need shared setup, use suite types with initializers, nested types, or suite-scoped helpers as appropriate to existing project patterns.
